<br>
Currently, if you taunt successfully, you end up with one point more hate than whoever was at the top of the list before the taunt. Theoretically, you could come into a fight extremely late, hit one Taunt, and the mob would turn on you. If you're already near the top of the hate list, taunt has less of a relative effect on your hate value.<br>
<br>
So change it to work this way... let's say for example that each player has a taunt value equal to around 2-3 times their Taunt skill level (perhaps modified by class so warriors get better Taunt skill than the others? not really important). When you successfully taunt, one of two things happens: If you are already near the top of the hate list (less than your value points away), you get your value added (so you end up several hundred points ahead of the next nearest person, keeping aggro more reliably). If you are farther down on the hate list, Taunt works just like it always has (putting you only one point ahead).<br>
<br>
With a system like that, procs would still be very helpful, but not a complete necessity like they are now. Two or three successful taunts would be sufficient to keep you at the top of the hate list so long as your dps and procs are not too far behind that of the people you have doing damage.<br>
<br>
Whether Sony would ever implement that, I dunno. It would certainly throw warriors a bone as far as their ability to hold aggro, but it may (in their eyes) somewhat trivialize the effort of dps classes on raids with regards to managing their own aggro.<br>
<br>
